content_chunks.content: The business models and value chains of the European construction sector must change to become the new engine of a green, digital, and sustainable European economy. Construction activities depend on construction information and on how people envision the buildings being created and can describe and communicate them to others. The construction sector is undergoing a paradigm shift from material-centric processes to data-centric processes. Digitalization must be purposeful and bring benefits to all stakeholders throughout the life cycle. Building Information Modeling (BIM) has become standard practice in the Estonian construction sector, predominantly in large consulting firms and construction companies, as well as in construction projects. However, the focus has been on the initial stages of the project life cycleâ€”that is, planning and designing construction projects in the BIM environment. In the preparation and management of construction processes, BIM is mainly used for clash detection, to some extent for quantity estimation, and for documenting the building and construction process. This, however, constitutes a small portion of BIM's potential in the preparation and management of construction work.

Building Information Modeling technology for construction management transformation - this course delivers advanced BIM methodologies for transitioning from material-centric to data-centric construction processes. Technology for construction management includes constructability analysis tools and design model preparation techniques, while 4D planning methods enable timeline visualization and construction sequencing optimization. The course introduces 5D planning tools for cost estimation and budget management, alongside BIM clash detection systems for conflict resolution in complex projects. Participants gain expertise in data management for construction, construction technology modeling, and as-is process monitoring techniques for real-time project oversight. The curriculum covers design model analysis for construction readiness, quantity estimation methods, and as-built documentation procedures for project completion verification. Students develop skills in BIM methodology implementation, construction process optimization through digital workflows, and enhanced stakeholder communication throughout project lifecycle. The course prepares professionals to leverage BIM's full potential beyond basic applications, implementing comprehensive digital strategies for improved project delivery, reduced errors, and enhanced collaboration in modern construction environments.
